Note:
SwiftUI Lexer - Tokenizes SwiftUI declarative UI code

This file provides lexical analysis for SwiftUI, Apple's declarative UI framework.
Handles SwiftUI-specific syntax including view declarations, modifiers, property
wrappers, and state management.

SwiftUI Structure:
- View structs with body property
- Declarative view composition (VStack, HStack, ZStack, etc.)
- View modifiers (.padding(), .background(), .foregroundColor(), etc.)
- Property wrappers (@State, @Binding, @ObservedObject, @Published, etc.)
- State and data flow
- Navigation and presentation
- Swift language features (closures, trailing closures, operators)

Token Types:
- Keywords (struct, var, let, func, some, View, etc.)
- Property wrappers (@State, @Binding, @ObservedObject, etc.)
- Built-in views (Text, Button, Image, VStack, HStack, etc.)
- Modifiers (identifiers starting with dot)
- Literals (strings, numbers, booleans, colors)
- Operators and delimiters
- Identifiers and type names

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_KEYWORD as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_PROPERTY_WRAPPER as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_MODIFIER as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_BOOLEAN as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_LPAREN as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_RPAREN as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_LBRACE as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_RBRACE as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_DOT as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 16
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 17
Constant TOKEN_SEMICOLON as Integer is 18
Constant TOKEN_ARROW as Integer is 19
Constant TOKEN_EQUALS as Integer is 20
Constant TOKEN_AT as Integer is 21
Constant TOKEN_DOLLAR as Integer is 22
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 23
Constant TOKEN_ERROR as Integer is 24

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A token record produced by next_token and consumed by the SwiftUI
parser. Carries enough metadata for parser-side recovery and
diagnostic reporting: type discriminator, the byte span pointing into
the original source (not an owned copy), and (line, column) of the
first byte. The lexeme pointer is shared with the source buffer so
the parser must not free the source for the lifetime of any token.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (5 x i64). Offsets: 0 token_type (TOKEN_* constant), 8
lexeme pointer (source + start_position), 16 lexeme_length, 24 line,
32 column. All fields are populated by create_token; ownership of the
record itself is the caller's.
@End Implementation
Type called "SwiftUIToken":
    token_type as Integer      Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer          Note: Pointer to lexeme string
    lexeme_length as Integer   Note: Length of lexeme
    line as Integer            Note: Line number
    column as Integer          Note: Column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lexer state for SwiftUI. Separates the live cursor (position, line,
column) from a saved token-start cursor (start_position, start_line,
start_column) so make_token can attach the correct location to a token
whose first byte was consumed many bytes ago. The 1-based line/column
convention follows editor expectations for diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
64-byte record (8 x i64). Offsets: 0 source (borrowed pointer to source
text), 8 source_length (cached at create), 16 position (byte cursor,
0-based), 24 line (1-based), 32 column (1-based), 40 start_position
(saved cursor at the start of the current token), 48 start_line, 56
start_column. Created only via create_swiftui_lexer; record ownership
is the caller's.
@End Implementation
Type called "SwiftUILexer":
    source as Integer          Note: Source code pointer
    source_length as Integer   Note: Source code length
    position as Integer        Note: Current position in source
    line as Integer            Note: Current line number
    column as Integer          Note: Current column number
    start_position as Integer  Note: Start position of current token
    start_line as Integer      Note: Start line of current token
    start_column as Integer    Note: Start column of current token
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates and primes the lexer record. source_length is cached once
via StringCore.string_length so the hot peek/advance path avoids
repeated length probes. position starts at 0, line and column start
at 1 to match editor 1-based diagnostics. The token-start cursors
mirror the live cursor so mark_token_start is never required before
the first scan.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source length, allocates 64 bytes; on OOM returns 0. Writes
source (offset 0), source_length (offset 8), zero position (offset
16), 1 line (offset 24), 1 column (offset 32), 0 start_position
(offset 40), 1 start_line (offset 48), 1 start_column (offset 56).
Returns the lexer record handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_swiftui_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create SwiftUI lexer

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Let lexer_size be 64  Note: SwiftUILexer: 8 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0   Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1   Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1   Note: column = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0   Note: start_position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, 1   Note: start_line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 1   Note: start_column = 1

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Examination
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming read of the current byte. Returns 0 at EOF so the
caller can branch on '== 0' rather than maintaining a separate
end-of-input flag. The source is assumed not to contain real NUL
bytes (SwiftUI/Swift source is conventional UTF-8 text).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position from offset 16 and source_length from offset 8. If
position >= source_length returns 0. Otherwise reads byte at
source+position via memory_get_byte.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-byte lookahead used for two-character tokens ("->" arrow, "//"
and "/*" comments, "*/" block-comment close). Reading past EOF
returns 0 like peek_char so the caller's branch logic stays uniform.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position from offset 16 and source_length from offset 8.
Computes target_pos = position + offset; if target_pos >= source_length
returns 0. Otherwise reads byte at source+target_pos. Offset is a
relative byte distance, not a token count.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_ahead" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek ahead at character at offset

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let target_pos be position plus offset

    If target_pos is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, target_pos

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes one byte and updates the line/column cursor. LF (10) is the
only newline form handled - the lexer treats CR (13) as whitespace
(see skip_whitespace) without resetting column, which is acceptable
because pure CR line endings are not used by modern macOS/iOS toolchain
output. This avoids double-counting "\r\n" as two lines.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads peek_char first so the routine can branch on the consumed byte
before mutating the cursor. Advances position by 1. On LF (10) bumps
line by 1 and resets column to 1; otherwise bumps column by 1.
Returns the consumed byte.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Note: Handle newlines
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: \n
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1
    Otherwise:
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column
    End If

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start classifier for SwiftUI. Swift permits Unicode
identifiers (S 2.5) but this lexer targets the ASCII subset that
covers the canonical SwiftUI corpus; non-ASCII identifier characters
fall through to TOKEN_ERROR. Underscore is included because Swift
identifiers may start with '_'.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
ASCII range checks: 65..90 ('A'..'Z'), 97..122 ('a'..'z'), or
exactly 95 ('_'). Each match returns 1; else 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: is greater than or equal to 'A'
        If char is less than or equal to 90:  Note: is less than or equal to 'Z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: is greater than or equal to 'a'
        If char is less than or equal to 122:  Note: is less than or equal to 'z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit classifier used both by scan_number (literal scanning)
and as part of is_alphanumeric (identifier-tail). Hex/binary/octal
literal prefixes (0x/0b/0o) are not implemented here; the bootstrap
SwiftUI corpus only needs decimal integers and floats.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Range check 48..57 ('0'..'9'); returns 1 on match, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: is greater than or equal to '0'
        If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: is less than or equal to '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-tail classifier: Swift identifier tail characters include
letters, digits, and underscore. Reuses is_alpha (which already
accepts underscore) so the routine is simply the OR of two specialists.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to is_alpha; on match returns 1. Else delegates to is_digit
and returns its boolean directly.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alphanumeric" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let alpha_check be proc is_alpha from char
    If alpha_check is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let digit_check be proc is_digit from char
    Return digit_check
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inter-token separator classifier. Includes space (32), tab (9), LF
(10), and CR (13). LF/CR both count as whitespace; the line-bumping
on LF happens inside advance_char so this classifier itself stays
location-agnostic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four equality checks against the four whitespace codepoints; returns
1 on any match, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:   Note: space
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 9:    Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 10:   Note: newline
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 13:   Note: carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Skip Whitespace and Comments
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Skips inter-token whitespace and both Swift comment forms (// to EOL,
/* ... */ block, no nesting because the bootstrap subset omits Swift's
nested-block-comment feature) in a single outer loop so the cursor
lands at the first interesting byte regardless of how comments and
whitespace are interleaved.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Outer infinite loop. Per iteration: if peek_char is_whitespace, advance
one byte and continue. Otherwise check for '/' at the cursor: '//'
enters a sub-loop consuming bytes until LF or EOF; '/*' enters a
sub-loop consuming bytes until '*/' or EOF (EOF terminates unclosed
block comments without error here - higher layers detect unmatched
sentinel). Anything else breaks the outer loop. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Source is untrusted; unbounded comment scanners are EOF-guarded so a
malformed unclosed block comment cannot spin past the buffer.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace and comments

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        Note: Skip whitespace
        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace from char
        If is_ws is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Skip line comments //
        If char is equal to 47:  Note: /
            Let next be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
            If next is equal to 47:  Note: another /
                Note: Skip until newline
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Let c be proc peek_char from lexer
                    If c is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
                        Break
                    End If
                    If c is equal to 10:  Note: newline
                        Break
                    End If
                    proc advance_char from lexer
                End While
                Continue
            End If

            Note: Skip block comments /* */
            If next is equal to 42:  Note: *
                proc advance_char from lexer  Note: skip /
                proc advance_char from lexer  Note: skip *

                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Set c to proc peek_char from lexer
                    If c is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
                        Break
                    End If

                    If c is equal to 42:  Note: *
                        Let next2 be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
                        If next2 is equal to 47:  Note: /
                            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: skip *
                            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: skip /
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If

                    proc advance_char from lexer
                End While
                Continue
            End If
        End If

        Note: No more whitespace or comments
        Break
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Heap-allocates a single 40-byte SwiftUIToken initialised from the five
caller-supplied fields. The token holds a borrowed lexeme pointer into
the source; this routine does not copy the bytes, so the caller must
preserve the source buffer until the token is freed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Layout.allocate(40); OOM returns 0. Writes token_type at offset 0,
lexeme pointer at offset 8, lexeme_length at offset 16, line at
offset 24, column at offset 32. Returns the new token handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, lexeme_length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token

    Let token_size be 40  Note: SwiftUIToken: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Snapshot the live cursor (position, line, column) into the
start_position/start_line/start_column slots so a subsequent make_token
attributes the produced token to the location of its first byte even
after the cursor has advanced through the token body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (16), line (24), column (32). Writes them to
start_position (40), start_line (48), start_column (56). Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "mark_token_start" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Mark start of new token

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, column

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Finalises a token using the snapshotted start cursor and the current
live cursor. The lexeme pointer is computed as source+start_position;
the length is current_position - start_position. This way scanners
need not carry the lexeme pointer/length manually - they just mark the
start once and let make_token compute the span.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source (0), start_pos (40), current_pos (16), start_line (48),
start_column (56). Computes lexeme = source + start_pos and
lexeme_length = current_pos - start_pos. Delegates to create_token
with (token_type, lexeme, lexeme_length, start_line, start_column).
@End Implementation
Process called "make_token" takes lexer as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token from current lexer state

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
    Let start_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56

    Let lexeme be source plus start_pos
    Let lexeme_length be current_pos minus start_pos

    Return proc create_token with token_type, lexeme, lexeme_length, start_line, start_column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a Swift string literal: opens with '"', closes with '"', allows
backslash escapes (the body of the escape is consumed as two bytes
without semantic interpretation - escape decoding is a later pass's
job). Unterminated strings and EOF inside the literal produce a
TOKEN_ERROR token so the parser can surface a diagnostic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Marks token start, then consumes the opening '"'. Loop body: EOF
(char 0) returns a TOKEN_ERROR token. Closing '"' (34) is consumed
and breaks. Backslash (92) is consumed; if the next byte is non-zero
it is also consumed as the escape payload. Otherwise the byte is
consumed plain. On clean exit make_token emits a TOKEN_STRING.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Source is untrusted; explicit EOF check inside the loop prevents
runaway scanning on unterminated literals.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "scan_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan string literal

    proc mark_token_start from lexer
    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: Skip opening quote

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR
        End If

        If char is equal to 34:  Note: closing "
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 92:  Note: backslash (escape)
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Let next be proc peek_char from lexer
            If next is not equal to 0:
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_STRING
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Number Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a numeric literal: integer body, optionally followed by '.' +
fractional digits. The '.' is only consumed as a decimal point if the
next byte is a digit; this prevents incorrectly absorbing
member-access dots like '0.padding' into the literal. No exponent or
suffix support because the bootstrap SwiftUI corpus only uses simple
decimal literals.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Marks token start. Outer integer-digits loop consumes is_digit bytes.
Peeks for '.'; if found, peek_ahead(1) is checked - on is_digit
consumes the '.' and runs a fractional-digits loop. Final make_token
emits TOKEN_NUMBER for both integer and float forms; the downstream
parser can split them by inspecting the lexeme bytes.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan number literal (integer or float)

    proc mark_token_start from lexer

    Note: Scan digits
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        Let is_dig be proc is_digit from char

        If is_dig is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Note: Check for decimal point
    Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Let next be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
        Set is_dig to proc is_digit from next

        If is_dig is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: skip .

            Note: Scan fractional part
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let c be proc peek_char from lexer
                Let is_d be proc is_digit from c

                If is_d is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                proc advance_char from lexer
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_NUMBER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword and Identifier Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an identifier/keyword/view-type lexeme. The caller has verified
the first byte is is_alpha; this scanner consumes the run of
is_alphanumeric bytes (which includes underscore via is_alpha) and
then delegates to classify_identifier to decide whether the lexeme is
a keyword, view type, boolean literal, or plain identifier.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Marks token start. Loop consumes peek_char while is_alphanumeric
returns 1. Tail-calls classify_identifier which produces the actual
token with the appropriate TOKEN_* discriminator.
@End Implementation
Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan identifier or keyword

    proc mark_token_start from lexer

    Note: Scan alphanumeric characters
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alphanumeric from char

        If is_alnum is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Note: Check if it's a keyword or view type
    Return proc classify_identifier from lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Decides which TOKEN_* discriminator to attach to an already-scanned
identifier lexeme. Swift reserved words and SwiftUI conventional names
(some, View, body, true/false, ...) become TOKEN_KEYWORD or
TOKEN_BOOLEAN. The capitalised SwiftUI view types (Text, VStack, ...)
become TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE - parser benefits from this lexical
discrimination because view bodies need to be parsed as DSL fragments.
Length-bucketing avoids redundant string compares against keywords of
the wrong length.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes lexeme pointer (source+start_position) and length
(current_position - start_position). Per-length branches call
check_keyword for each reserved word of that length; on match emits
the appropriate token type via make_token. After all keyword checks
fail, delegates to check_view_type for the capitalised view-type
namespace. Unmatched lexemes fall through to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Implementation
Process called "classify_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Classify identifier as keyword, view type, or identifier

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be current_pos minus start_pos

    Let lexeme be source plus start_pos

    Note: Check SwiftUI keywords
    If length is equal to 4:
        Note: "some", "View", "body", "func"
        Let matches_some be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "some", 4
        If matches_some is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If

        Let matches_view be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "View", 4
        If matches_view is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If

        Let matches_body be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "body", 4
        If matches_body is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If

        Let matches_func be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "func", 4
        If matches_func is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If

        Let matches_true be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "true", 4
        If matches_true is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_BOOLEAN
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 3:
        Note: "var", "let"
        Let matches_var be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "var", 3
        If matches_var is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If

        Let matches_let be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "let", 3
        If matches_let is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 5:
        Note: "false", "State"
        Let matches_false be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "false", 5
        If matches_false is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_BOOLEAN
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 6:
        Note: "struct", "import"
        Let matches_struct be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "struct", 6
        If matches_struct is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If

        Let matches_import be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "import", 6
        If matches_import is equal to 1:
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check view types (Text, VStack, HStack, ZStack, Button, Image, etc.)
    Let is_view be proc check_view_type with lexeme, length
    If is_view is equal to 1:
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE
    End If

    Note: Regular identifier
    Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

@Reasoning:
Byte-equal string comparison specialised to the keyword-check use case.
Length mismatch short-circuits to 0 because callers have already
length-bucketed but pass the keyword's length anyway as a sanity guard.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Length compare; mismatch returns 0. Byte-by-byte loop via
memory_get_byte; any mismatch returns 0. Falls off the loop returning
1 only when every byte matches.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(L) in the lexeme length but length-bucketing in callers keeps the
amortised cost dominated by short keywords (3-6 bytes).
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "check_keyword" takes lexeme as Integer, lex_len as Integer, keyword as Integer, key_len as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if lexeme matches keyword

    If lex_len is not equal to key_len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be 0
    While index is less than lex_len:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme, index
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with keyword, index

        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifies SwiftUI built-in view type names: Text, VStack, HStack,
ZStack, Button, Spacer, Image, Color, Rectangle. The lexer classifies
these distinctly from regular identifiers because the SwiftUI parser
treats their occurrence as the start of a declarative view expression
(eligible for the trailing-closure DSL form). Length-bucketing keeps
each lookup O(1) in keyword count.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Per-length switch with check_keyword calls. Length 4: Text. Length 5:
Image, Color. Length 6: VStack, HStack, ZStack, Button, Spacer.
Length 9: Rectangle. Any match returns 1; falls through to 0
otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_view_type" takes lexeme as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier is a SwiftUI view type

    Note: Common view types: Text, VStack, HStack, ZStack, Button, Image, etc.

    If length is equal to 4:
        Let matches be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "Text", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 6:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "VStack", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Let matches2 be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "HStack", 6
        If matches2 is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Let matches3 be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "ZStack", 6
        If matches3 is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Let matches4 be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "Button", 6
        If matches4 is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Let matches5 be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "Spacer", 6
        If matches5 is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 5:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "Image", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Set matches2 to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "Color", 5
        If matches2 is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 9:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "Rectangle", 9
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Token Scanner
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Main scanner entry. Skips whitespace and comments, then dispatches by
the first byte: punctuation (single-char delimiters), '->' (arrow,
needs lookahead), '=' (equals), '"' (string), digit (number), alpha
(identifier/keyword/view). Unknown bytes produce TOKEN_ERROR so
unrecognised input does not stall the lexer indefinitely.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls skip_whitespace then peek_char. EOF (char 0): mark and emit
TOKEN_EOF. Each punctuation byte (40 '(', 41 ')', 123 '{', 125 '}',
91 '[', 93 ']', 46 '.', 44 ',', 58 ':', 59 ';', 64 '@', 36 '$') is
its own branch that marks, advances, and emits the matching TOKEN_*.
For '-' the routine checks peek_ahead(1) == '>' to emit TOKEN_ARROW
(consuming both bytes). '=' emits TOKEN_EQUALS. '"' delegates to
scan_string. Digits delegate to scan_number. is_alpha delegates to
scan_identifier. Fallthrough marks, advances one byte, emits
TOKEN_ERROR.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Source is untrusted; the TOKEN_ERROR fallthrough ensures unrecognised
bytes can never spin the lexer because each iteration consumes at
least one byte before re-entering the dispatcher (caller is expected
to surface TOKEN_ERROR as a diagnostic and continue).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from source

    proc skip_whitespace from lexer

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

    Note: Check for EOF
    If char is equal to 0:
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF
    End If

    Note: Single character tokens
    If char is equal to 40:  Note: (
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_LPAREN
    End If

    If char is equal to 41:  Note: )
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_RPAREN
    End If

    If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACE
    End If

    If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACE
    End If

    If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACKET
    End If

    If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACKET
    End If

    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOT
    End If

    If char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_COMMA
    End If

    If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_COLON
    End If

    If char is equal to 59:  Note: ;
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    End If

    If char is equal to 64:  Note: @
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_AT
    End If

    If char is equal to 36:  Note: $
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOLLAR
    End If

    Note: Multi-character tokens
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Let next be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
        If next is equal to 62:  Note: >
            proc mark_token_start from lexer
            proc advance_char from lexer
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_ARROW
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 61:  Note: =
        proc mark_token_start from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_EQUALS
    End If

    Note: String literals
    If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Return proc scan_string from lexer
    End If

    Note: Numbers
    Let is_dig be proc is_digit from char
    If is_dig is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_number from lexer
    End If

    Note: Identifiers and keywords
    Let is_alph be proc is_alpha from char
    If is_alph is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_identifier from lexer
    End If

    Note: Unknown character
    proc mark_token_start from lexer
    proc advance_char from lexer
    Return proc make_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR
End Process

Note: End of SwiftUI Lexer
